The vulnerability stems from unsafe deserialization in React's Flight protocol, impacting server component payloads in versions 19.0.0, 19.1.0, 19.1.1, and 19.2.0 of various packages, including `react-server-dom-parcel`, `react-server-dom-turbopack`, and `react-server-dom-webpack`. Exploitation is possible under default configurations of popular frameworks such as Next.js, React Router, and Waku.

Google Threat Intelligence Group (GTIG) observed widespread exploitation of CVE-2025-55182 shortly after its disclosure, with activity ranging from opportunistic cybercrime actors to suspected espionage groups. Proof-of-concept exploits have been made public, and the vulnerability has been added to the CISA Known Exploited Vulnerabilities (KEV) catalog. Attacks have included the deployment of cryptocurrency miners (like XMRig) and attempts to establish persistence, as well as enumeration of system details, environment variables, lateral movement, and credential theft targeting cloud services like Azure, AWS, and GCP. Microsoft Security has also reported on the vulnerability, noting that exploitation was detected as early as December 5, 2025.

While there is extensive information regarding CVE-2025-55182 and its active exploitation, there are no search results directly linking the IP address "193.32.162.28" to this specific vulnerability as a known exploited host or an attacker's infrastructure. The IP address "193.32.162.28" is part of the "193.32.162.0/24" IP range, which is associated with AS47890 UNMANAGED LTD, but no specific security reports or compromise details related to this IP and CVE-2025-55182 were found."""
